						span.article__dropcap--intro uinzell Covington went on a shooting “caper” for the first time with his cousin and friends,
						span  the “tough guys” who raised him in ways of the streets. Afterward, over Chinese takeout, he tried to ingratiate himself with the crew by assuring them that their victim “got what he deserved.”
					p He was 13 years old. Growing up in a “pretty good family,” he knew it was wrong to shoot a man. Still, he said, “I really didn’t feel any remorse or anything.” What he did feel was that his crew had a "newfound respect” for him.
					p By 14, he was the one doing the shooting. Over time, he learned to do it well. He used 9mm guns that held 16 bullets and Mac-10 submachine guns with extended clips. He lured victims to his turf, where he could scout for witnesses and surveillance cameras, in what he called his “Miranda check” -- a macabre reference to the right to remain silent.
					p He also knew where to aim.

		section#chapter-1
