					p “If I shoot you in the leg, I know what I’m going to get,” he said. “If I shoot you in the stomach, I know what I’m going to get. If I shoot you in the head, I definitely know what I’m going to get. I’m going to get your demise.” 
					p Covington’s evolution encapsulates a larger trend driving gun violence around the country -- increasingly, people are shooting to kill. In Baltimore, one of every three people struck by gunfire dies. That means it ranks as the most lethal of America’s largest cities, according to a Baltimore Sun analysis.
					p Two other cities -- Washington, D.C., and New Orleans -- shared the brutal distinction of a one-in-three gun homicide rate in 2015. Several cities have seen the death grip tighten. In Chicago, one in 10 people died after being shot in 2000; now one in five perish.                   
					p Last year turned particularly lethal -- the odds for gunshot victims worsened in 10 of the nation’s largest cities, The Sun found in a review of available data. 
					p On the streets, cities are witnessing more lethal tactics. Police and hospitals are reporting surges in head shots and victims who have been shot repeatedly. Criminals are stockpiling higher-caliber guns, many with extended gun magazines that hold dozens of bullets. And trauma doctors are finding it more difficult to save gunshot victims.
					p The result: In many places, if you get shot, you are more likely to die than ever before.

