					p The Baltimore Sun documented these patterns of lethality in a yearlong investigation based on available crime statistics, hospital data and gun trace reports as well as interviews with police chiefs, homicide detectives, criminologists, epidemiologists, community activists, victims of gun violence and the perpetrators themselves.
					p Historically, gun violence research in the U.S. has been inhibited by a lack of federal funding and data -- many police departments only track what they are required to report to the FBI each year, which doesn’t include include how often people survive shootings, where on the body people are shot and how many times.
					p That has led to a focus on annual body counts and homicide rates, which can be traced back nearly a century, and left criminologists to puzzle over the causes behind spikes and dips.  
					p Over the past two years, a number of cities -- Baltimore, Chicago, Milwaukee, New Orleans, Washington -- have been gripped by a steep increase in shootings and homicides. Deteriorating police-community relations have been blamed, as have gang conflicts and entrenched societal ills such as segregation, poverty and joblessness.
					p While all these factors play a role in driving violence across the nation -- as they have for years, if not decades -- a city’s homicide rate typically fluctuates, sometimes significantly. Just five years ago, Baltimore public officials were celebrating a drop in the annual homicide count below 200. This year, that marker was crossed in August.
					p But one trend has been constant: Lethal force has become more so.

					
