					p More shooters are aiming for the head and firing multiple rounds into victims. In Baltimore, roughly two-thirds of homicide victims are either shot in the head or multiple times. Many suffer both fates.
					p Head shots have increased fivefold in the city over the past two decades, to more than 60 percent of victims. And the number of bodies with XX or more bullets has XX in the past decade, according to the Maryland medical examiner’s office, which tallied the grim statistic at the request of The Sun.
					p Guns also have become more deadly, as the weapon of choice for criminals and then law enforcement shifted from the revolver to the semi-automatic. Nationally, the number of 9mm and .40-caliber guns taken off the streets surged over the past four years, as seizures of the less powerful .22-caliber guns remained relatively flat.
					p In Maryland last year, seizures of 9mm handguns overtook .22-caliber guns for the first time since statistics started being kept a few years ago. Most were on Baltimore’s streets, where the saying goes: “Buy every gun that comes through; don’t let it be the gun that kills you.”
					p Many of the guns are equipped with extended magazines, allowing a shooter to fire from a distance and “walk down” a victim, continuously firing. Banned in Maryland, where clips are limited to 10 rounds, these “extendos” are prized in street cultures where long magazines are tucked under belts and into pants as a fashion statement.
					
