					p Metropolitan Police Chief Cathy L. Lanier, who is retiring this month after more than a decade in Washington, D.C., keeps a photo of a 100-round magazine seized by police on her cellphone as a reminder of the firepower out there.
					p Law enforcement officials across the country also say they’ve observed more insidious circumstances that are difficult to quantify. Reckless shootings in the daytime. Vigilante justice and contract killers. Gang rules that codify when violence should be used -- and street rules that limited violence against innocent bystanders being broken.
					p While shooter motives vary, experts and those caught in the crossfire note a ruthlessness on the streets where hardened criminals with more sophisticated weaponry aren’t just using guns to intimidate rivals or carry out robberies. They are using them to take people out.
					p “It’s very common for someone to walk up and empty a pistol at close range,” said criminologist David M. Kennedy, describing the “extreme” gang mindset in cities like Baltimore, Washington and New Orleans. “It’s organization, it’s a street ethos, it’s very likely retaliation. It’s going in with a heightened intent to actually kill you.”
					p Guns are stashed in trash cans, hung from gutter grates by a string and stashed in other nooks around cities where they can be quickly recovered when needed. (Covington says he kept part of his arsenal under an apartment complex’s washing machine.)
					p Or young men with clean records are serving as “human holsters” for felons, according to Milwaukee Police Chief Edward A. Flynn.
					p In Baltimore, police are tracking the so-called 10 Grand Club, an organized gang of hitmen willing to kill for that price, and prosecutors say that’s double the typical fee. (Covington became a contract killer but also says he “killed out of friendship” for free if a woman approached him about taking out her rapist or her child’s molester.)
					p Not even decades of advancements in trauma medicine can stem the carnage.
					p Gunshot victims have seen their chances of survival plummet, even as patients with major injuries from other assaults and car accidents have seen their chances improve dramatically. Studies by hospitals and trauma centers across the country, including Baltimore’s top-ranked medical systems, have documented this contrarian trend.
					p “We feel this represents a true change in violence intensity,” Johns Hopkins Hospital researchers concluded.
					p This has left communities nationwide reeling, with violence concentrated in poor, predominantly black neighborhoods where mothers are forming support groups, not only to help each other cope but in a desperate search for ways to stop the killing. A nationwide network of grief is starting to form.
					p “We’re all facing similar dynamics,” said Corneilius Scott, who volunteers as executive director of Mothers of Murdered Sons and Daughters in Baltimore. “There’s a lot of concern and not many answers.”
					p At the group’s meetings, parents are talking about “sensitizing” young men to the effects of violence. They believe -- and social science is finding -- that their boys need to be taught empathy, lest they become trapped in a cycle, repeatedly exposed to violence and becoming more likely to commit it.

