					p Rodney Chase sensed trouble when three young men approached him on Gay Street in Baltimore, but he didn’t run, saying he’s not the kind to back down from anyone. One of the men pulled a gun; they wanted his NFL Starter jacket, his wallet, anything of value.
					p As Chase took off his jacket, one of the men tried to yank it off, and Chase instinctively hit him. The gunman fired into Chase’s belly, and Chase felt as if hot grease had been thrown at him.	
					p A woman nearby screamed and called an ambulance. He underwent surgery. Doctors put in a screen under his skin to hold in his organs. He wasn’t discharged for nearly two months. All from a .22 caliber gun.
					p “Luckily it was a .22,” he said recently, lifting his shirt to show off a scar slicing down the middle of his stomach. “I’m grateful for that. If it was bigger, I’d be done.”
					p That was more than two decades ago. Had he been shot nowadays, with the kinds of guns prevalent on Baltimore’s streets, he believes he’d be dead.
					p He knows Baltimore’s streets because that’s where he’s spent most of his life. He was a drug addict living in an abandoned house earlier this year when he was seriously injured in a knife attack and ended up at the University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center. He also was admitted into a hospital program that connects patients with social services in hopes of reducing the recidivism of violence.
					p “I call it ‘Clip City,’” Chase said of Baltimore. “What they got now -- they’re death dealers. And it’s not hard to get ‘em.
					p Gun production in the U.S. set a blistering pace in recent years.
					p The manufacturing of pistols, revolvers, rifles and shotguns has grown steadily since 2008, to 10.8 million in 2013 and more than 9 million firearms in 2014, according to the the latest data from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives.
					p That’s double and triple the annual pace of manufacturing in the previous 20 years.
					p Moreover, the guns sold now are more powerful. They are higher caliber weapons, discharge bullets at faster speeds and come with larger magazines. 
					p “All of these factors, over the last several decades, have progressed,” said Jay Wachtel, a 20-year ATF agent who is now a professor of criminal justice at California State University at Fullerton. That has led to what he called an “incredible increase in the lethality of guns.”
					p Even an inexperienced shooter, Wachtel said, can do a lot of damage with a high-caliber semiautomatic gun, which can fire more bullets without reloading than a revolver. “You don’t need to be a very good shot because any organs nearby are going to be pulverized,” he said.
					p Gun experts have wondered about the reasons driving sales. Some say fear of stricter gun control is stoking demand; others say law-abiding citizens are arming themselves in the wake of mass shootings.
					figure.inline-media.inline-media--pic.inline-media--full(data-sr)
						img(src="dist/images/ex1.jpg")
						figcaption.inline-media--pic__caption Caption goes here
						btn.inline-media--pic__open-gallery OPEN GALLERY
					p Eventually, though, many of those guns end up on the streets despite state and national laws aimed at keeping guns out of the hands of felons. Law enforcement officials in cities nationwide say they have seen an increase in the quality of guns wielded by criminals.
					p “All the cheap guns made in the 80’s have either quit functioning or have been recovered by police,” said Los Angeles Homicide Det. John Skaggs, the protagonist in the best-selling book “Ghettoside” for his determination to solve homicide cases. “They seem to all be expensive and high-quality now.”
					p In Milwaukee, police are tracking this trend.
					p In 2006, the top three guns seized by police there were the Hi-Point 9 mm and .380 pistols that cost less than $200 and have standard magazines that hold eight bullets as well as the Mossberg 12-gauge shotgun that sells for about $320.
					p About halfway through 2016, the most seized gun was the the Smith & Wesson .40-caliber pistol that costs more than $400 and comes with a magazine that holds as many as 16 rounds, followed by the Smith & Wesson 9 mm pistol and the Glock .40-caliber handgun -- both of which sell for more than $500 and have standard magazines that hold nine to 15 bullets.
					p “The gun of choice of street offenders has shifted over time to higher quality, higher caliber of semiautomatic pistols,” said Kennedy, the criminologist who directs the National Network for Safe Communities, a project of John Jay College of Criminal Justice in New York City. “Since those are the guns that gangs and drug-involved offenders are more likely to have, they’re more likely to kill somebody.”
					p Flynn, Milwaukee’s police chief, said most of the guns used in crime -- nearly 90 percent -- are bought legally. He blamed “straw purchases,” in which someone with a clean criminal record buys the gun for felons who are banned from owning a firearm, as well as street sales.
					p He said the average time from when a gun is purchased to when it is recovered by law enforcement dropped from 10.6 years in 2012 to 8.6 years in 2014, indicating a quicker pace at which guns are trickling into the hands of criminals.
					p “Everyone assumes they’re stealing the guns,” Flynn said. “They're buying them legally.”
					p In Baltimore, the once-ubiquitous “Saturday night specials” -- cheaply made 22- or .25-caliber handguns that were banned for a time in Maryland -- are no longer as prevalent.
					p Now 9mm guns are the top gun seized by police, and the Glock .40 caliber was most often used in crimes last year. Those weapons are capable of firing a bullet nearly twice the diameter of the original Saturday Night Special.
					p “A lot of big guns out there,” said James “J.T. Timpson, a community liaison officer with Safe Streets, the city’s violence mediation program that works in high-crime neighborhoods to resolve conflicts without police intervention. “We don’t have .22s no more.”
					p Timpson said shooters believe they need “stopping power” to ensure their mark is dead -- and can’t retaliate.

