					p Measures aimed at limiting high-capacity magazines haven’t kept them off the streets, either.
					p The 1994 federal assault weapons ban, which expired in 2003, restricted magazines to no more than 10 rounds of ammunition. As Congress grappled with whether to renew the law, the Department of Justice studied its effectiveness.
					p The researchers focused in part on Baltimore, which has kept a wider range of crime data than other cities. During the ban, they found no decline in the number of guns with extended magazines being used in violent crimes in the city, including homicides, shootings, robberies and other assaults.
					p Maryland again restricted the number of bullets guns can carry when lawmakers passed one of the nation’s strictest gun control laws in 2013. The law, which regulates certain gun purchases, also prohibits the sale and possession of detachable magazines of more than 10 rounds.
					p Since the law passed, however, dozens of “extendos” have been confiscated in the city. Baltimore gun seizures are up XXX, but police don’t track the capacity of magazines on guns they’ve recovered.
					p As for the law’s effectiveness, that’s difficult to track. Only 11 people have been charged in Baltimore under the magazine statute. One possible reason: It’s still legal to possess large-capacity magazines if they were purchased outside the state.
					p The penalties under the law are stiff. If convicted of committing a felony or violent crime with an extended magazine, defendants face a minimum of five years in prison and a maximum of 20. 
					p In neighboring D.C., where gun seizures by police are up nearly 50 percent this year over last, police noticed more rounds being shot at scenes, from multiple shooters, and with high-capacity magazines. So they began keeping statistics.
					p Last year, about one-third of guns recovered had high-capacity magazines. Through June of this year, nearly half had large clips. 
					p At the same time, after years of steep declines in the nation’s violent crime rate, homicides spiked in Washington, Baltimore and more than half of the largest American cities last year. That higher pace has continued in MANY? cities this year.
					p Former D.C. Chief Lanier, who worked with police chiefs across the U.S., sharing ideas and data, said it’s clear from what she’s seen in Washington and what she’s heard from her counterparts in other cities that shootings are becoming more lethal.
					p According to an analysis by The Sun, the odds for gunshot victims worsened last year in a number of cities including Washington as well as Detroit, Louisville, Charlotte and San Francisco. In New York, one in five shooting victims died last year, up from one in seven in 2014. In Nashville, the odds of dying increased from one in nine shootings in 2014 to one to four last year.
