					p That surprised XXX researcher from Harvard University, who said he would have thought as the number of shootings surged, the rate at which people died would decline.
					p This lethality rate is an overlooked aspect of the homicide equation that researchers say they’d like to explore but are hampered by a paucity of statistics. The Sun reviewed statistics from half of the 30 largest cities; police departments in the other cities don’t track the data, making a nationwide analysis impossible.
					p Researchers said lethality is a significant piece of the puzzle, with implications for policing, public health and trauma care.
					p Lanier blames the pernicious state of cities on the brazen nature of some of the attacks. Criminals are emptying their clips, she said, leaving crime scenes littered with 50 to 60 shell casings, and opening fire in the daytime.
					p “Something’s changed in the mentality of the people shooting,” Lanier said. “Very reckless. Everyone’s got a gun, and everyone is willing to do these shootouts.”
					 
