					p The first bullet ripped into his thigh, and he crumpled.
					p Devante Fordbey dropped to the asphalt on a spring day two years ago, when he turned and saw his assailant in a hoodie pointing what looked like a .9mm. The gun was jammed, and Devante began pulling himself up the street on his elbows and forearms as quick as he could. Then he heard the next shot blast.
					p Now the bullets felt like hammer blows. The more the shooter closed in, the more he felt the force of the bullets moving at more than 900 feet per second. Fordbey turned onto his back and put his hands up.
					p “You’re good, you’re good!” Fordbey yelled. “You got me!”
					p But the shots kept coming. A bullet pierced his inner left pectoral muscle. Nine sunk into his right thigh. One just missed his heart, striking his chest where the words “Nana” for his grandmother are tattooed along with some clouds and doves.
					p Figuring he was going to die, he began to taunt the shooter. “You’re a bitch.”
					p Then a slug sliced into his head, and he blacked out just as he saw the man run away. He figures his survival instinct must have taken over, and he came to as he was trying to crawl away again.
					p “He heard me shuffling on the ground, and I’m trying to get myself off the ground,” Fordbey said. “He came right back and slapped in another clip in the gun. Boom. Boom. Boom. Boom. … I blacked out.”
					p In and out from consciousness he went, while his mother dug out the slug from his skull and pressed her hand against his neck to stop the bleeding. She lived nearby and came running when word reached her.
					p “I’m sorry ma. I’m sorry ma. I feel myself leaving, I feel it,” he told her.
					p As a paramedic called his name in the racing ambulance, he thought it was God. “Devante! Devante! Devante!”
					p With advancements in trauma medicine over decades, emergency room patients now have a better chance of surviving than ever before. Patients who have been stabbed are more likely to live. Better care coupled with safety advancements have driven deaths from motor vehicle accidents to historic lows.
					p Gunshot victims, however, are less likely to live.
					p In Baltimore, at the University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center, the nation’s first hospital devoted to trauma injuries, doctors sought to assess improvements in care. They studied patients over a dozen years and found that chances for surviving “improved significantly.”
					p A notable exception: gunshot victims. In 1999, 9.8 percent of those patients died. By 2008, that rate had risen to 17 percent.
					p The study’s authors, including Thomas Scalea, the physician-in-chief at center, blamed the increasing availability of lethal automatic and semiautomatic weapons on the street. Today, Scalea says that trend has continued. The trauma surgeon is seeing more “higher velocity injuries” from high-caliber guns and more bullet wounds per patient.
					p Johns Hopkins Hospital also studied trauma outcomes and found that the fatality rate for patients with gunshot wounds rose from 9.5 percent between 2000 and 2003 to 18.3 percent for the period through March 2005.
					p And most of them died in the emergency room. For those patients doctors and nurses were able to stabilize and move out of the trauma bays, the fatality rate remained stable at 5 percent during both periods. The study concluded that the overall fatality rate jumped because more patients were arriving in grave shape.
					p More patients were dead on arrival, and more succumbed to their injuries within minutes of arriving at the hospital. The median time before they were pronounced dead: six minutes.
					p The researchers also noted another grim statistic: About half of patients were shot in the head, and the already slim chance of survival for those patients narrowed over time. In fact, the researchers at one of the nation’s most respected medical institutions concluded there was little they could do.
					p “The only way to save these patients is to reach out to them in the community before they are victims of violence,” the study concluded.

