					p On the streets, gunmen were increasingly aiming the head. It has been a clear, long-term trend in Baltimore, with the number of fatal head shots rising steadily from about 13 percent of homicide victims in 1994 to 62 percent last year.
					p Some criminals are cunning enough to know that more of their targets are wearing body armor, said Baltimore police Maj. Donald Bauer. And In a cruel twist, some shooters are taking into account that Baltimore has top-notch trauma care, said former police commissioner Anthony Batts. That’s why they aim for the head -- to “take the trauma center out of the equation.”
					p “When they’re trying to take someone out, they shoot them in the head,” said Batts, now a consultant with the AWW Group training police commanders.
					p Gunmen also were increasingly pumping bullets into victims. People shot multiple times made up less than 60 percent of homicide victims in 2005, the earliest year for which data is available. That rose to 70 percent by last year.
					p The Maryland Office of the Chief Medical Examiner recently studied homicide autopsy reports of gunshot victims dating to 2005. About one-third of the victims died from a single gunshot, and that remained constant over the past decade. But when victims were shot multiple times, the number of bullets per cadaver steadily increased from 4.7 in 2005 to 5.7 last year.
					p “I never get a single gunshot wound -- never,” said Sue Carol Verrillo, nurse manager of the surgical inpatient care unit at Johns Hopkins Hospital.
					p Hospitals and medical schools across the nation have witnessed the same trends -- the severity of wounds and the sheer number of them increase year by year. 
					p Angela Sauaia, professor of public health, medicine, and surgery at the University of Colorado Anschutz Medical Campus, was among a team of researchers that recently completed a study of patients at a Denver trauma hospital, comparing chances of survival from various injuries.
					p Again, they found that gunshot victims stood out for falling behind. Their fatality rate jumped 6 percent -- every two years. When patients were taken to Denver Health Medical Center, survival rates didn’t improve at all during the time period studied -- 13 years, starting in 2000.
					p “There are more injuries to treat so no wonder the case fatality is increasing,” Sauaia said. “That was not the norm 10 years ago.”
					p Doctors couldn’t keep up with the increasing trauma. “We do know there are more bullets, and the injuries of each bullet are more serious,” she said. “The holes are bigger.”
					p In Newark, New Jersey, researchers were seeing the same. Over a dozen years through 2011 at the New Jersey Trauma Center at University Hospital, the percentage of patients with three or more wounds doubled, as did those with injuries to three or more body regions. The incidence of brain and spinal cord injuries almost doubled.
					p Researchers also noted more gunshot victims were arriving at the emergency room in the afternoon and evening, when there was still some daylight left and witnesses were more likely to be awake.
					p And again, researchers found, the mortality rate increased.
					p Fordbey, now 24, was one of the lucky ones. Shot 27 times, he had been a victim, he says, of “karma” after years of percocet-popping, drug dealing, fights and shootouts.
					p He saw his shooter and believes he was targeted by a rival drug crew over turf. Fordbey toyed with the idea of retaliating -- gathering his “boys,” finding the suspect, and shooting him and everyone with him, leaving no witnesses.
					p But he says he gave up “the game” to focus on being a father to his four children. He’s re-learned how to walk with extensive physical therapyand keeps the bullet his mother dislodged from his head in a box near his bed.
					p Still, he isn’t about to give up his credibility on the streets.
					p “I can’t be labeled a snitch. I can’t be labeled a rat, especially in this city,” he said, explaining why he didn’t cooperate with police. “Snitches die.”
					p “Code of the streets period,” he added. “Snitches get stitches. I honor the street code -- the G code. I honored it my whole life. I can’t tolerate snitching. I can’t. My body, my mindset won’t let me tell.”
					p No one has ever been arrested in his shooting.
					 
		section#chapter-4
			.container-story
