					p Criminals today know to get close to their target and fire a lot of bullets, said Stuart Myers, a former police officer who runs Op-Tac International, which trains law enforcement in Maryland and elsewhere on weapons and tactics. That’s because most criminals aren’t good shots, he said.
					p Even police officers, who train and are certified, miss their targets more than they hit them. One study put the average hit rate for officers at less than 30 percent. 
					p “If you’re close enough to a target, you could close your eyes and pull the trigger,” Myers said. He estimated that range is within three yards. Then, he said: “You will hit your target.”
					p Police say a common tactic shooters use to gain proximity is to work work with an accomplice who knows the target. The accomplice lures the target to an area, putting the person at ease to ensure a blind-side.
					p In gang parlance, it’s known as “rocking you to sleep.”
					p Shooters also are reaching for high-caliber guns with large magazines to ensure they hit their mark, said Dante Barksdale, an outreach coordinator for Safe Streets.
					p “The more bullets that they got the safer that they are,” he said. “They know they can’t hit nobody from two blocks away. They got to get up on you.”
					p Barksdale knows the streets. He spent eight years in prison for heroin dealing. His uncle is Nathan “Bodie” Barksdale, a legendary Baltimore drug dealer whose life inspired characters in the television show “The Wire.”
					p In some neighborhoods, he said friends or drug crews pool money to buy guns, often bought at gun shows or stolen from registered gun owners, and they become shared weapons on a given street corner.
					p Adding an extended clip is not only key to survival, “it’s an obsession,” according to Chris Wilson, who started the residential and commercial contracting company Barclay Investment Corp. in Baltimore, working with local agencies? to give ex-offenders jobs and help them start businesses.
					p “In the streets when you get a gun, you got to put an extended on it. You got to. That’s policy. You got to be official,” said Wilson, who grew up in Washington, where he dealt drugs and was in more than a dozen shootouts. He was sentenced to life in prison at 17 after he shot and killed a man. He served nearly 15 years.
					p In a shootout, it can be a simple matter of math. “A car rolls up, they fire some shots, you fire six or seven back, then they fire shots, you might get pinned down and you have to shoot back to get out of there,” Wilson said. “If you have nine or 10 bullets, you’re out.”
					p The larger clips also allow a shooter to “walk you down,” said Timpson, of Safe Streets.
					p “If I start further back, that means I have to be more accurate,” he said. “But if I start with an extendo, and I hit you from the corner, I’m going to walk you down. … I can walk you down without ever having to stop firing.”
					p Former Baltimore Deputy Police Commissioner Jerry Rodriguez, who has spent nearly 30 years in law enforcement, mostly with the Los Angeles Police Department, said he was struck by the “level of determination” among killers in Baltimore. He noted the high number of head shots.
					p “I think there’s a meaning behind that. I think there’s a purpose behind that,” he said. “It’s sending a message, but it’s also making sure the outcome is what they want.”
					p Rodriguez, now a consultant to police departments, said he found “a much more personal type of killing in Baltimore” -- a city of 92 square miles -- compared to Los Angeles that sprawls over 470 square miles.
					p But even on the West Coast, police have noted a shift in shooting dynamics. In Los Angeles, gangs have often carried out drive-by shootings, which could be indiscriminate and ineffective if the intent is to kill someone in particular.
					p Now, they are getting out of the car.   
					p “You want to kill ‘em, not wing ‘em,” said LAPD Homicide Det. Chris Barling, describing the mentality of shooters.

 

